kse.utilclass.sets

Class ArraySet<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractSet<E>
        • kse.utilclass.sets.ArraySet<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - element type of this container class
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Set<E>, OperatingSet<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SortedArraySet

    public class ArraySet<E>
extends java.util.AbstractSet<E>
implements OperatingSet<E>, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable
    ArraySet is a java.util.AbstractSet which implements the package own OperatingSet interface for convenient set operations. Each member object can only be contained once and it allows null to be an element. It also works as a Collection.

    The advantage of ArraySet over a TreeSet can be seen in the instant availability of the conversion into an array, or in its block data structure which causes less heap segmentation. There is, however, a disadvantage in higher cardinalities, and in particular with the set operations, for their execution time.

    Complexities (of the implementation of this class)
    Single item: insertion costs O(1), iteration, removal and membership cost O(n) execution time, with n = size(). Set operations (s1, s2) (OperatingSet) cost O(n*m) with n=|s1|, m=|s2|.

      • elementData

        protected transient java.lang.Object[] elementData
        The array buffer into which the elements of the ArrayList are stored. The capacity of the ArrayList is the length of this array buffer. Any empty ArrayList with elementData == DEFAULTCAPACITY_EMPTY_ELEMENTDATA will be expanded to DEFAULT_CAPACITY when the first element is added.
